What I tell my non-American friends
CAMBRIDGE – I travel frequently abroad and my foreign friends ask me each time, with varying degrees of perplexity: but what is happening in your country then ?
Here's what I tell them.
Firstly, be careful not to misunderstand the 2016 elections.
Contrary to certain comments, the American political system was not swept away by a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against the elites.
Donald Trump exploited the vein of a tradition associated with leaders like Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
Yet Trump missed winning the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the elections by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If a hundred thousand votes had been cast differently in those states, Trump would have lost the electoral college and the presidency.
However, Trump's victory raises the real issue of the rise of social and regional inequalities in the United States.
The latest bestseller by J.D. Vance, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the great difference between California and the Appalachians.
Research by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among low-income whites without college degrees are worse than those of African Americans, who historically sat at the lower end of inequalities.
In 1999, mortality rates among whites without higher education were about 30% lower than those of African Americans; in 2015, they were 30% higher.
Furthermore, employment in the manufacturing industry, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for working-class whites, has declined sharply over the past generation, to just 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were attracted by Trump's promises to shake things up and bring back jobs in the industry.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation may well make their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is not to underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his Twitter rants and his scandalous disdain for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality TV, where he learned that the key to success is to monopolize the attention of the audience, and the best way to do that is to make extreme statements, without worrying about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract from his critics.
What annoys commentators in the media and academic circles does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his self-centered campaign to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that deters some allies he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who fails to win the popular vote would move towards the political center to attract more support.
That's what George W. Bush did successfully in 2001.
Trump, on the other hand, claims he won the popular vote and by acting as if it were really the case, pleases his core voters.
Although Trump made solid centrist nominations to the Department of Defense, State, and National Security, his choices for the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Health and Human Services are at the extremes of the Republican Party.
His White House staff is divided between ideologues and pragmatists - and he intends to satisfy both camps at the same time.
Fourthly, one should not underestimate the American institutions.
Sometimes my friends speak as if the sky is falling on their heads and ask me if Trump is as dangerous a narcissist as Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
The United States, despite its many problems, is not Italy in 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but the founders of America were just as divided.
In the design of the United States Constitution, the founders' goal was not to ensure that the government is harmonious, but to limit political power to a system of checks and balances that makes it difficult to exercise those powers.
A joke about this says that the founders created a political system so that King George couldn't rule over us - couldn't him or anyone else.
Inefficiency has been put at the service of liberty.
Trump's presidency is still in its early stages, and we can't be certain about what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
However, so far, the courts, Congress, and the states have maintained this balance of power within the administration, as Madison had envisioned.
And the permanent executive branch bureaucrats still wield their weight.
Finally, my friends wonder what all this means for American foreign policy and the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Frankly, I don't know, but I worry less about China's rise to power than about Trump's.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about free riders, the United States has long been at the forefront in providing important global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite the problems of the international order under US leadership, the world has prospered, and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can claim with certainty that this will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational issues.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first major-party candidate in 70 years to question the American alliance system.
Since taking office in January, Trump's and his team's statements suggest that he may persist in this challenge.
The United States' power to constrain and persuade other countries, after all, comes largely from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has only a few).
However, the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's common goods, is more uncertain.
Trump's Budget Director talks about a power-constraining budget, with budget cuts made to the State Department and the United Nations system.
Other government members advocate for replacing multilateral trade agreements with "fair and balanced" bilateral arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change.
I tell my friends that I would like to reassure them on these issues.
But I cannot.
